Drexel Days

In 1985, Marc moved to New York and started his new job as an associate in =
Drexel=E2=80=99s M&A group, of which Leon was the head. According to Marc, =
Drexel=E2=80=99s class of =E2=80=9985 featured =E2=80=9Ca great cast of cha=
racters,=E2=80=9D including the David Solomon, who worked in commercial pap=
er, and the current C.E.O. of Jefferies, Rich Handler, who worked in privat=
e placements. Marc=E2=80=99s boss was Alison Mass, a banking vice president=
 (with whom I worked at Merrill), who is now a senior partner at Goldman Sa=
chs.

Marc immediately grasped the intricacies of finance and accounting=E2=80=94=
the Lotus 1-2-3 modeling, the difference between purchase and pooling accou=
nting (back when that mattered), and consolidations. =E2=80=9CYou graduate =
from school and you have no idea whether you=E2=80=99ve learned anything,=
=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CAnd I got to
Drexel, and it all made sense. Literally, I just knew how to do it. I worke=
d like a dog.=E2=80=9D

While Goldman offered blue-chip prestige, Drexel offered opportunity. =E2=
=80=9CSeniority meant nothing,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt was all about =
brain power.=E2=80=9D Marc worked for clients such as Charles Hurwitz on hi=
s successful takeover of Pacific Lumber, which owned one of the oldest grov=
es of old-growth redwood trees. (=E2=80=9CI remember going in a helicopter =
on a survey of the logging in the Pacific Northwest,=E2=80=9D he told me.) =
He worked for Ron Perelman, putting together the financing for what became =
his acquisition of Revlon. He worked for John Malone and TCI, his cable beh=
emoth. He worked for Marvin Davis on his acquisition of Spectradyne. He wor=
ked for Jack Nash, at Odyssey Partners, and for KKR. =E2=80=9CI worked for =
everyone,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI was a good utility player.=E2=80=9D

For her part, Mass found Marc to be demonstrably
brilliant from the start. =E2=80=9CHe was just so intellectually curious an=
d high energy=E2=80=94like literally high energy, and in an infectious way,=
 in a good way,=E2=80=9D she told me. At the time, the banking teams at Dre=
xel were chronically understaffed, mainly because few people wanted to work=
 there. =E2=80=9CWe were still the underdog,=E2=80=9D Mass recalled. =E2=80=
=9CYou were always thrown out a little farther than you were comfortable.=
=E2=80=9D

The Hotel California

Things started to change for Marc and Drexel after the stock market crashed=
 on October 19, 1987, plummeting 22.6 percent=E2=80=94still the largest sin=
gle-day decline in history. Michael Milken called Marc up to say he wanted =
him to move to Los Angeles the very next day to help Drexel =E2=80=9Cwork d=
own our balance sheet risk.=E2=80=9D

Marc arrived late at night at the Four Seasons in Beverly Hills only to fin=
d that his room had been given away. The horrified manager drove Marc to th=
e Beverly Wilshire for the night, and upon his return to the Four Seasons t=
he next day, Marc was informed that his room had been upgraded. The manager=
 asked him when he=E2=80=99d be checking out. =E2=80=9CMay,=E2=80=9D Marc r=
eplied.

For months, he lived at the Four Seasons like Eloise at the Plaza. He sat n=
ear Milken and his famous X-shaped desk=E2=80=94which was for traders=E2=80=
=94in
Drexel's Beverly Hills office. By then, the lines between M&A and leveraged=
 finance had blurred. Marc=E2=80=99s new job was to sell the leveraged loan=
s that Drexel had underwritten through private placements of the debt. =E2=
=80=9CThese were complex transactions,=E2=80=9D he told me. He would spend =
hours on the phone trying to sell the debt of Drexel's corporate clients to=
 Drexel's investing customers, such as Columbia Savings and Loan, Fidelity,=
 T. Rowe Price, and Executive Life.

Milken would walk by his desk every day and ask him an outside-the-box ques=
tion=E2=80=94often on Saturday mornings at 4:30 a.m., when Milken demanded =
that the team be in the Beverly Hills office. Why, for instance, did the de=
ep coal mine owned by Jim Walter Corporation have value? =E2=80=9CMike=E2=
=80=99s questions were always about where the puck was going. And he was ac=
tually, and still is, a very inspirational person for just thinking about t=
he bigger context. It=E2=80=99s not about this thing. It=E2=80=99s about wh=
y this thing is
going to be successful, and why the trends in the world are going to make t=
his successful. And it was actually an incredibly useful framework for how =
to think about the world, for how to think about where we are. For me, it w=
as pivotal.=E2=80=9D

Of course, Drexel exploded in 1989 after Milken was indicted on 98 counts o=
f fraud, racketeering, and all manner of financial wrongdoing. Drexel=E2=80=
=99s clients and customers lost confidence in the firm, and it became yet a=
nother casualty of borrowing short and lending long. Milken went to prison =
after pleading guilty to a fraction of the charges against him. (Trump pard=
oned Milken at the end of his first term.) Marc moved back to New York and =
eventually found himself again working for Leon at the start of their new f=
irm, Apollo. He married Carolyn Pleva, a fashion designer. They have four a=
dult children, but have been living apart for years. The rest, I suppose, i=
s history.

Rational Choice Theory

If Trump chooses Marc, it will be the most rational decision that the presi=
dent-elect has made since descending the escalator at Trump Tower, in June =
2015. There are a few other contenders still in the mix, along with Marc. T=
here=E2=80=99s U.S. Senator Bill Hagerty, a former private-equity investor,=
 who has been gaining altitude on Trump=E2=80=99s shortlist. (Apparently he=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cgreat on TV.=E2=80=9D) There is also former Fed governo=
r Kevin Warsh, who is also expected to meet with Trump at Mar-a-Lago this w=
eek, although Trump may be keeping Warsh in reserve as Fed chairman once Ja=
y Powell=E2=80=99s term is over. And then there is Marc=E2=80=94a dark hors=
e in some ways, but surely the most impressive of the three.

In the meantime, to share a sense of Marc=E2=80=99s negotiating strategy, h=
e recently bought an old restaurant in Orient Point on the North
Fork of Long Island. It=E2=80=99s now known as Duryea=E2=80=99s Orient Poin=
t, a sister restaurant to the main Duryea=E2=80=99s, in Montauk, which Marc=
 also owns. Marc had his attorney, former state judge Edward Burke Sr., dra=
ft the papers to seal the purchase deal. =E2=80=9CBut the judge and I have =
a saying, =E2=80=98Don=E2=80=99t buy anything until there=E2=80=99s ice on =
the ground,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Marc once told Shawn Tully at Fortune. =E2=80=
=9CEveryone is very optimistic in the Hamptons in the summer, and they get =
less optimistic when it gets cold.=E2=80=9D

