          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In 1985, Marc moved=
 to New York and started his new job as an associate in Drexel=E2=80=99s M&=
amp;A group, of which Leon was the head. According to Marc, Drexel=E2=80=99=
s class of =E2=80=9985 featured =E2=80=9Ca great cast of characters,=E2=80=
=9D including <i>the</i> <b>David</b> <b>Solomon</b>, who worked in commerc=
ial paper, and the current C.E.O. of Jefferies, <b>Rich</b> <b>Handler</b>,=
 who worked in private placements. Marc=E2=80=99s boss was <b>Alison</b> <b=
>Mass</b>, a banking vice president (with whom I worked at Merrill), who is=
 now a senior partner at Goldman Sachs.<br/><br/>Marc immediately grasped t=
he intricacies of finance and accounting=E2=80=94the Lotus 1-2-3 modeling, =
the difference between purchase and pooling accounting (back when that matt=
ered), and consolidations. =E2=80=9CYou graduate from school and you have n=
o idea whether you=E2=80=99ve learned anything,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9C=
And I got to
Drexel, and it all made sense. Literally, I just knew how to do it. I worke=
d like a dog.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>While Goldman offered blue-chip prestige, =
Drexel offered opportunity.  =E2=80=9CSeniority meant nothing,=E2=80=9D he =
said. =E2=80=9CIt was all about brain power.=E2=80=9D Marc worked for clien=
ts such as <b>Charles</b> <b>Hurwitz</b> on his successful takeover of Paci=
fic Lumber, which owned one of the oldest groves of old-growth redwood tree=
s. (=E2=80=9CI remember going in a helicopter on a survey of the logging in=
 the Pacific Northwest,=E2=80=9D he told me.) He worked for <b>Ron Perelman=
</b>, putting together the financing for what became his acquisition of Rev=
lon. He worked for <b>John Malone</b> and TCI, his cable behemoth. He worke=
d for <b>Marvin</b> <b>Davis</b> on his acquisition of Spectradyne. He work=
ed for <b>Jack</b> <b>Nash</b>, at Odyssey Partners, and for KKR. =E2=80=9C=
I worked for everyone,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI was a good utility play=
er.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>For her part, Mass found Marc to be demonstrably
brilliant from the start. =E2=80=9CHe was just so intellectually curious an=
d high energy=E2=80=94like literally high energy, and in an infectious way,=
 in a good way,=E2=80=9D she told me. At the time, the banking teams at Dre=
xel were chronically understaffed, mainly because few people wanted to work=
 there. =E2=80=9CWe were still the underdog,=E2=80=9D Mass recalled. =E2=80=
=9CYou were always thrown out a little farther than you were comfortable.=
=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
